2.10	We recommended that:
1.	The Municipal Accountant –
Prepares the necessary adjusting entries for the Due to BIR account;
Withheld from each employee the amount of tax deficiency covering the CY 2024 supplementary compensation, and henceforward, avoid the same miscalculation;
2.	The Municipal Treasurer remits the tax deficiencies noted on compensation income for CY 2024.

3.6	We recommended that:
a.	LCE executes Job Order contracts between the Municipality and the hired JOs, specifying therein the following: wage rate, work duration, functions/duties, that there is no employer-employee relationship between the parties, and that work rendered is not considered as government service;
b.	The JO personnel submit approved DTRs, supported with authenticated copies of the logbook/biometric printouts, and Accomplishment Reports certified correct by the officials who have direct supervision over their work, specifying in detail the work accomplishments for the particular period;
c.	The OIC-HRMO/officials concerned/direct supervisors ensure that the hired JOs are faithfully reporting their log-in and log-out entries in their DTRs, and are performing their respective work assignments/duties, as indicated in their job order contracts; and
d.	The Municipal Accountant ensures the completeness of supporting documents for the payments of wages to JO workers.

1.27	We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant Designate –
Exert effort to trace back details of PPE acquisitions, recompute the accumulated depreciation of the CY 2022 reported balance of depreciable assets taking into account the appropriate residual value for each PPE, and the pertinent provisions in COA Circular No. 2015-008 and PAG3.  Thereafter, effect the necessary adjustments upon determination of the correct amounts, for the proper valuation of the PPE;
Reclassify the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts after verification;
Transfer the PPEs booked up in the TF to the GF, upon completion of projects/purpose of the fund transfer, and depreciate the assets;
Reclassify the assets erroneously recorded as Office Equipment to the ICT Equipment account; and
Maintain complete PPE ledger cards/subsidiary records for items of PPE and coordinate with the Property Officer/Inventory Committee for the identification of recorded assets that were not accounted in the RPCPPE.  Undertake reconciliation of records, to accurately and reliably present the PPE accounts in the financial statements.
The Property Officer/ Inventory Committee Chairperson –
Compare existing records with the Municipal Accountant-Designate for tracing/identification of PPE which were not accounted in the RPCPPE, and reconcile PPE items and their balances between the accounting and property records;
Prepare and maintain complete Property Cards;
Include real properties in the physical count of PPE; and
Communicate to the Municipal Accountant-Designate the result of the physical count of PPE to update his records.
1.28	We further recommended that management conduct a One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances, following the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to address the problem of unidentified PPE items in the accounting records and discrepancies in PPE account balances, which have become a perennial issue and caused the non-establishment of the accuracy of the PPE balances presented in the financial statements.

11.6	We recommended that:
LCE executes Job Order contracts between the Municipality and the hired JOs, specifying therein the following: wage rate, work duration, functions/duties, that there is no employer-employee relationship between the parties, and that work rendered is not considered as government service;
The JO personnel submit approved DTRs, supported with authenticated copies of the logbook/biometric printouts, and Accomplishment Reports certified correct by the officials who have direct supervision over their work, specifying in detail the work accomplishments for the particular period;
The OIC-HRMO/officials concerned/direct supervisors ensure that the hired JOs are faithfully reporting their log-in and log-out entries in their DTRs, and are performing their respective work assignment/duties, as indicated in their job order contracts; and
The Municipal Accountant Designate ensures the completeness of supporting documents for the payments of wages to JO workers.
11.7 	The Municipal Administrator and the OIC-HRMO noted the above deficiencies and committed to comply with the recommendations.
